    <h2>Non-Functional Requirements</h2>

    <h3>Platform</h3>

    <p>The CourseSmart server should run on Solaris/Unix. It should be as portable to
      other Unix systems as reasonably feasible but it need not run on any other Unix
      system at this time. The client should run on modern Microsoft Windows systems
      (2000, XP). Wide client portability is desirable.</p>

    <h3>Performance</h3>

    <p>Command response times should be short enough so that interactive users are not
      annoyed by any delays. In general delays should limited to network transfer time.</p>

    <h3>Security</h3>

    <p>It is important that students be unable to modify the course materials, see quizzes
      before they are released by the instructor, see each other's submissions and grades,
      or modify their own grades. The system should resist denial of service attacks by
      students. The system need not be secure against a malicious instructor.</p>

    <h3>Reliability</h3>

    <p>The system should have good reliability characteristics. System down time should be
      due, in most cases, to network failure or server host machine failure and not due to
      server or client software failure.</p>

    <h3>User Characteristics</h3>

    <p>Students and instructors can be assumed to have average general computer skills. It
      will be helpful if instructors are able to author HTML documents (outside of
      CourseSmart). Users will interact with the system frequently.</p>

    <h3>Scale</h3>

    <p>The system should support a single course containing at most 50 to 100 students and
      perhaps two or three instructors. Arbitrary static limits should be avoided when
      possible so that the system has the potential of being pushed beyond these limits if
      necessary.</p>

    <h3>Data</h3>

    <p>The system does not need to be compatible with any existing course support package;
      data formats can be choosen free of constraints. Network protocols can also be
      freely choosen.</p>

    <h3>Internationalization</h3>

    <p>There are no internationalization requirements.</p>

    <h3>Environmental</h3>

    <p>There are no environmental requirements.</p>

    <h3>Expected Changes</h3>

    <p>Support for multiple courses and support for other client platforms are the most
      likely changes.</p>

    <h3>Delivery Date</h3>

    <p>Early December 2004. Lateness is impossible.</p>

